Introduction

This summer, our lab was introduced to the plankton splitter used to equally split a sample in half in order to identify the ideal 300-500 organisms instead of 1,000+ macroinvertebrates in full samples. The microhabitat UFR (upstream, fast, rocky) of the green sample taken on 6/5/23 was the first to be split into UFR-A and UFR-B using the plankton splitter. However, UFR-A looked noticeably larger than UFR-B, leading to the question, how accurate is the sample split in terms of biodiversity and number of organisms?

UFRA <- read_sheet('https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/13MoLbg5kr-mFca_SZFZ7gkKXPzbD6z-XN3jWmyI6cmI/edit#gid=0')

Graphing

ggplot(
  data = UFRA,
  mapping = aes(x = number)
) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggtitle("Graph 1 \nVisualizing UFR-A")

ggplot(
  data = UFRB,
  mapping = aes(x = number)
) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ggtitle("Graph 2 \nVisualizing UFR-B")

By graphing UFR-A and UFR-B in box plots, we are able to compare the interquartile range, middle 50% of the data, and visualize the outliers in order to assess variability. In UFR-A, Chironomidae larva totaled at 353 organisms, and Segmented_worms totaled at 63. In UFR-B, Chironomidae larva totaled at 294 organisms, and Segmented_worms totaled at 42. Due to these outliers, the data is very variable and will offer a less precise conclusion. Therefore, in order to best visualize the difference in biodiversity and total organisms in the split sample, we have to remove these values.

Analysis

Biodiversity

In terms of biodiversity, the graphs of UFR-A and UFR-B without outliers appear to have a similar biodiversity visualized by the spread of the variables. UFR-A is slightly more diverse at 21 genera compared to the 20 genera identified in UFR-B. In UFR-A, Acentrella, Torleya, Baetis, Glossosomatidae, and Lanthus genera were identified that were not found in URF-B. And similarly, in UFR-B, Polycentropus, Antocha, Nematomorpha, and Trombidiformes genera were identified that were not found in UFR-A.

Number of Organisms

In terms of the number of organisms, the graphs of UFR-A and UFR-B without outliers separated by life stage appear to have a similar values visualized by the shape of the graph. Majority of the identified genera in both UFR-A and UFR-B differ by 0-1 organisms. However, there are 5 genera that have a difference greater than 1, including Pycnopsyche, Neophylax, Psephenus, Stenonema, and Leucrocuta. Specifically, the difference in Leucrocuta identified in UFR-A is double than that identified in UFR-B, and is visibly skewing the shape. Similarly, but excluded from the graph, UFR-A has a higher number of both Chironomidae larva and Segmented Worms than UFR-B. Including these families, UFR-A has a total of 502 organisms and UFR-B has a total of 406 organisms.

Conclusion

Through analysis, I claim that neither biodiversity or number of organisms are significantly impacted by splitting the sample. However, based on the data from sample UFR, I conclude that the plankton splitter is not accurate in separating samples into two equal halves. Of the 5 genera only observed in UFR-A, 4 are identified as clinger/swimmers, and 1 is identified as a burrower. While of the 4 genera only observed in UFR-B, 2 are identified as swimmers, 1 is identified as a clinger, and 1 is identified as a burrower. Clingers tend to be found in larger debris, while swimmers and burrowers tend to be found in sediment. Categorizing the macroinvertebrates by movement patterns suggests that the reason for observing different genera in the split sample is because of the visibly disproportionate divide of sediment and debris. The significance of identifying different genera between the split sample is that it could impact the accuracy of assessing water quality. In UFR-A, the 5 identified genera have sensitivity grades of 3.6, 2.9, 3.6, 5.0, and 3.0, fairly sensitive on the scale from 1-10 where 1 is most sensitive and 10 is most tolerant. Comparatively tolerant, the 4 genera in UFR-B have sensitivity grades of 5.0, 4.5, 6.0, and 6.0. Similarly, the accuracy of assessing water quality can be impacted by the frequency of the identified genera. The genera Pycnopsyche, Neophylax, Psephenus, and Leucrocuta that were more frequently observed in UFR-A than in UFR-B are all identified as clingers, while the genus Stenonema, more frequently observed in UFR-B than in UFR-A, is identified as a clinger/swimmer. The sensitivity ratings of the frequently observed genera in UFR-A have an average sensitivity grade of 2.75, compared to the frequently observed genus in UFR-B with a sensitivity grade of 3.0. Even with a similar biodiversity and number of organisms, the overall sensitivity grade for UFR-A appears to be lower than the sensitivity grade for UFR-B, suggesting better water quality in UFR-A than in the UFR-B, despite being two halves of the same sample.

Possible Errors

As previously noted, UFR is the first sample to be split using the plankton splitter, and could have experienced challenges with the new equipment or new user. To more accurately assess the plankton splitter, we can split more samples and similarly identify and compare the organisms in both halves.
